    <div class="dec-card">
      <div class="dec-head">
        <div class="dec-num">1</div>
        <div class="dec-title">Unsupervised vs. Supervised ML</div>
      </div>
      <div class="dec-body">
        <div class="options-row">
          <div class="opt rejected">
            <div class="opt-label rej">Rejected</div>
            <strong>Supervised (Labeled Fraud Data)</strong><br>High precision — but no labeled fraud dataset existed. 12–18 months of data collection needed before training.
          </div>
          <div class="opt selected">
            <div class="opt-label sel">Selected</div>
            <strong>Unsupervised (Statistical Anomaly)</strong><br>No labels needed. Learns from all historical invoices immediately. Detects novel patterns.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="rationale">Label scarcity is the real-world constraint. Unsupervised delivers value on Day 1.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="dec-card">
      <div class="dec-head">
        <div class="dec-num">2</div>
        <div class="dec-title">HANA Vector DB vs. External Vector Store</div>
      </div>
      <div class="dec-body">
        <div class="options-row">
          <div class="opt rejected">
            <div class="opt-label rej">Rejected</div>
            <strong>Pinecone / Weaviate</strong><br>Purpose-built, high performance — but invoice data cannot leave SAP infrastructure per enterprise governance policy.
          </div>
          <div class="opt selected">
            <div class="opt-label sel">Selected</div>
            <strong>HANA Vector DB</strong><br>Native to existing stack. No data egress. SOC2-compliant by default. Performance immaterial at ~500-document scale.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="rationale">Choosing SAP-native infrastructure eliminated 4 integration risks and accelerated IT stakeholder buy-in.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="dec-card">
      <div class="dec-head">
        <div class="dec-num">3</div>
        <div class="dec-title">GenAI Explanations vs. Template-Based Explanations</div>
      </div>
      <div class="dec-body">
        <div class="options-row">
          <div class="opt rejected">
            <div class="opt-label rej">Rejected</div>
            <strong>Template-Based</strong><br>"CTL-047 failed because value exceeds threshold." — Binary, technical, no path to action for AP Managers.
          </div>
          <div class="opt selected">
            <div class="opt-label sel">Selected</div>
            <strong>LLM-Generated Natural Language</strong><br>Context-rich explanation + resolution steps + new control suggestion. Reduces escalation rate.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="rationale">Explainability is the single highest-leverage UX decision. An anomaly score without context is noise.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="dec-card">
      <div class="dec-head">
        <div class="dec-num">4</div>
        <div class="dec-title">Auto-Block HIGH Risk vs. Flag Only</div>
      </div>
      <div class="dec-body">
        <div class="options-row">
          <div class="opt rejected">
            <div class="opt-label rej">Rejected (as sole option)</div>
            <strong>Flag Only</strong><br>Zero disruption — but reviewers may deprioritize flags; anomalies still release to payment.
          </div>
          <div class="opt selected">
            <div class="opt-label sel">Selected</div>
            <strong>Risk-Tiered Response</strong><br>LOW → auto-approve. MEDIUM → review queue. HIGH → auto-block + immediate notification.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="rationale">One-size-fits-all blocking creates AP team fatigue. Tiered response matches action severity to risk level.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>


