      <div class="sec-title">Lessons Learned</div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson">
      <div class="lesson-tag">Stakeholders</div>
      <div class="lesson-body">
        <strong>Stakeholder Alignment</strong>
        AP Managers needed to see <em>what changes for them on Day 1</em> — not the ML architecture. Led with the exception queue UX, not the model design. Adoption velocity correlated directly with personal value visibility.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="lesson">
      <div class="lesson-tag">Data</div>
      <div class="lesson-body">
        <strong>Data First</strong>
        Running feature analysis on TIPA sample data before finalizing model type saved 3+ weeks of rework. The data had more structure than expected, enabling richer features and higher model precision from the start.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="lesson">
      <div class="lesson-tag">Product</div>
      <div class="lesson-body">
        <strong>Controls as a Product</strong>
        Treating the 165 controls as a <em>product backlog</em> — with performance metrics, owners, and a promotion pipeline — reframed the problem from "engineering task" to "product discipline." This framing unlocked buy-in from both AP team and IT.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="lesson">
      <div class="lesson-tag">UX</div>
      <div class="lesson-body">
        <strong>Explainability is UX</strong>
        The decision to invest in GenAI explanations early — even before the core ML model was production-ready — was the single highest-leverage UX decision in the project.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="lesson">
      <div class="lesson-tag">Enterprise</div>
      <div class="lesson-body">
        <strong>Enterprise Constraints are Features</strong>
        Choosing SAP-native infrastructure (HANA Vector DB, AI Core, Data Sphere) eliminated 4 integration risks, simplified data governance, and accelerated stakeholder buy-in from IT teams already managing those platforms.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>


